# Security Group Rules — Three-Tier Web Application

## ALB Security Group (alb-sg)
| Type | Protocol | Port | Source | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Inbound | HTTP | 80 | 0.0.0.0/0 | Public web traffic |
| Inbound | HTTPS | 443 | 0.0.0.0/0 | Secure web traffic |
| Outbound | All | All | 0.0.0.0/0 | Allow all outbound |

## Web Tier EC2 Security Group (web-sg)
| Type | Protocol | Port | Source | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Inbound | HTTP | 80 | alb-sg | Traffic from ALB only |
| Inbound | HTTPS | 443 | alb-sg | Traffic from ALB only |
| Inbound | SSH | 22 | Your IP only | Admin access |
| Outbound | MySQL | 3306 | db-sg | Connect to RDS |
| Outbound | HTTPS | 443 | 0.0.0.0/0 | AWS API calls (S3, etc.) |

## RDS Security Group (db-sg)
| Type | Protocol | Port | Source | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Inbound | MySQL | 3306 | web-sg | Web tier DB access only |
| Outbound | None | — | — | No outbound needed |

## Key Security Principles Applied
- RDS is in private subnets — no direct internet access
- EC2 only accepts traffic from ALB, not directly from internet
- SSH restricted to specific IP (not 0.0.0.0/0)
- Database port only open to web tier security group
